SIMPLE: penumbra
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Penumbra
<hw>Pe*num"bra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. L.
<ets>paene</ets> almost + <ets>umbra</ets> shade.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>An incomplete or partial shadow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>The shadow cast, in an eclipse,
where the light is partly, but not wholly, cut off by the intervening
body; the space of partial illumination between the umbra, or perfect
shadow, on all sides, and the full light.</def> <rj><au>Sir I.
Newton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The faint shade surrounding the dark central portion of
a solar spot is also called the <altname>penumbra</altname>, and
sometimes <altname>umbra</altname>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <def>The part of a picture where the
shade imperceptibly blends with the light.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Penumbrala</ent>⟦br⟧
